<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How do I calculate crown molding for a room?", answer: "Measure the room perimeter: 2 × (length + width). For a 12 × 14 ft room that is 52 linear feet. Subtract any door openings where the molding stops (typically 3 ft each for a standard interior door). Add 10-15% for waste from miter cuts, corner joints, and imperfect pieces. Divide by your stick length (8, 10, 12, or 16 ft) and round up to get the number of sticks to buy." },
  { question: "Does crown molding run over doors?", answer: "In most residential work, yes — crown molding is continuous around the room, including over door headers. This gives a cleaner look than stopping at each doorway. If you do stop the molding at openings, subtract the opening widths from the perimeter. The calculator supports both with the door openings input — enter 0 to run continuous, or enter total opening widths to deduct." },
  { question: "How much waste should I add for crown molding?", answer: "10% for simple rectangular rooms with few corners. 15% for rooms with many corners, returns, or cathedral ceilings where you have to custom-cut angled pieces. 20% if you are new to crown molding — bad cuts are common the first few pieces. Buying a little extra is always cheaper than running back to the lumber yard mid-project." },
  { question: "What stick lengths should I buy?", answer: "Longer sticks (14, 16 ft) minimize joints but are harder to handle and transport. 12 ft is the most common compromise. 8 ft works in small rooms where you cut the full wall length from one stick. Always try to span each wall with a single stick to avoid joints; plan the layout before buying." },
  { question: "Are inside and outside corners different?", answer: "Yes — inside corners are typically coped (one end cope-cut to fit the profile of the adjoining piece) rather than mitered. Outside corners are always 45° miters. Coping prevents gaps that open up as the wood moves seasonally. Plan to cope only one end per stick and leave the other end square or mitered for the next corner." }
]) %>

